				<p><span class="style10">SPEAKER ABSTRACTS </span><br><br><br>

				  <strong><span class="style17">Daniel Scherman, PhD</span><br>

				  </strong><em>Department of Exploratory Research, G&eacute;n&eacute;thon, &Eacute;vry, France</em><strong><br>

                  </strong> <span class="style10"><br>

                  <img src="images/conference/8-Scherman.jpg" width="135">                  <br>

                  <br>

                  <br>

                  <strong>The potential of plasmid electrotransfer</strong></span><br>

                  <br>

                  Several  techniques have been investigated to deliver genes by physical techniques. They  include: naked DNA, gene gun, hydrodynamic delivery (tail vein, arterial or leg  vein injection), electrotransfer, focused ultrasound mediated gene delivery, and  laser induced plasmid delivery. We and others had reported very efficient  plasmid DNA transfer in muscle fibers using square-wave electric pulses of low  field strength (less than 300 V/cm) and of long duration (more than 1 ms).This  intramuscular &ldquo;electrotransfer&rdquo; method increases reporter and therapeutic gene  expression by several orders of magnitude in various muscles and species, and  decreases inter-individual variability. The five following aspects will be  reviewed. <strong><em>Mechanism of intramuscular electrotranfer</em></strong>. We will describe  a new combination of pulses, which leads to similar gene transfer efficiency,  while being likely less deleterious since it delivers less energy to muscle  tissue and leads to lower electro-permeabilization. Thus, a combination of  pulses of various strength and duration represents a new procedure for skeletal muscle gene  transfer, which is potentially improved in view of further clinical  development. Moreover, these results give insights on the mechanism of DNA  entry into the cells submitted to appropriate electric pulses.&nbsp;<strong><em>Sustained  plasmatic protein secretion</em></strong>. Sustained secretion of reporter protein  secreted alcaline phophatase, for more than 12 months, will be reported. Other  secreted proteins such as Factor IX were also detected at high concentration in  the systemic circulation after I.M. electrotransfer.&nbsp;<strong><em>Physiological  effect after I.M. electrotransfer of erythropoietin encoding plasmid</em></strong>.  I.M. electrotransfer of a pCMV EPO plasmid led to an increase of approximately  10- to 100- fold in circulating murine erythropoietin level, as compared to  naked DNA alone. Using electrotransfer, as little as 1 mg of an erythropoietin  encoding plasmid was sufficient to induce an increase in mouse hematocrit, from  47% up to 80%. This hematocrit increase was stable over at least two months.  Moreover, inter-individual hematocrit variability was highly reduced by  electrotransfer, as compared to that obtained with naked DNA injection. Moreover,  electrotransfer of these pCMV EPO plasmid leads to a marked improvement of  beta-thalassemic mouse hematocrit.&nbsp;<strong><em>Non viral gene therapy by electrotransfer  of hTNF-&alpha; soluble receptor-I variants and its application to the treatment of  experimental arthritis</em></strong>. Electrotransfer has been used to administer  transgenes encoding three human TNF-&alpha; soluble receptor-I (hTNFR-Is) variants.  Electrotransfer parameters and therapeutic effect in collagen-induced arthritis  (CIA) in mice were studied. Methods: The following three plasmids were used:  pCOR hTNFR-Is, encoding a monomeric form of TNF receptor; pCOR hTNFR-Is/mIgG1,  encoding a chimeric form of TNF receptor; and dimeric pCOR (hTNFR-Is)2,  encoding a dimeric form of TNF receptor. After I.M. electrotransfer, local  expression in the muscle lasted for at least 6 months, with similar levels for  the three forms. On the other hand, the plasmatic concentration of chimeric  receptor was 100 fold higher than the other forms, presumably because of rapid  elimination of the monomeric and dimeric forms of TNF receptor&nbsp;by renal  clearance.&nbsp; While electrotransfer of  monomeric or dimeric forms led to no clinical benefit, electrotransfer of the chimer  encoding plasmid led to a clear-cut decrease of clinical signs and histological  signs of arthritis. Repeated recombinant protein (etanercept) injections  highlighted the interest of the gene therapy approach, which leads to sustained  therapeutic effect after single treatment. The potential applications for the  treatment of rare genetic diseases will be discussed.&nbsp;<br>

</p>

